      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Body Corporate Insurance When Selling a Queensland Apartment or Townhouse
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Buyers of strata property ask more questions about building insurance than most sellers anticipate. Understanding what the body corporate insurance covers, what it costs, and whether the building is adequately insured puts you in a better position when those questions arise.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>When you sell a unit or townhouse in a Queensland community titles scheme, the buyer is not just acquiring your lot. They are also acquiring a proportional stake in the body corporate, including ongoing exposure to how the body corporate manages its insurance obligations. For buyers who intend to finance their purchase, their lender will require evidence that the building is adequately insured before approving the loan. For buyers who are self-funding, an understanding of the insurance position is increasingly part of their due diligence. Sellers who know their building's insurance position before listing are better prepared to answer questions and less likely to face mid-campaign uncertainty.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What body corporate insurance is required to cover in Queensland</h2>
      <p>Under the Body Corporate and Community Management Act 1997 (Qld), the body corporate is required to insure the building and common property. This insurance must cover the replacement value of the building, including all lots and common property, and must protect against the full range of insurable events including fire, storm damage, water damage, and other material damage risks. The insurance is compulsory: a body corporate cannot choose to self-insure or to carry no insurance.</p>

      <p>The insurance covers the building structure, common property improvements such as pools, gardens, lifts, and common area facilities, and common area contents. It does not cover the individual lot owner's personal contents inside their lot, the lot owner's fixtures and fittings that are not part of the building structure, or the lot owner's personal liability for events that occur inside their own lot rather than on common property. Sellers should understand this boundary clearly, because buyers sometimes assume the body corporate insurance is broader than it is.</p>

      <p>Individual lot owners are responsible for insuring their own contents and for obtaining their own public liability insurance for events within their lot. In the context of a sale, this means the body corporate insurance and the seller's personal insurance are two separate matters, and both need to be confirmed before settlement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the insurance levy covers and how to find the figure</h2>
      <p>A portion of each lot owner's quarterly administration fund levy goes toward paying the body corporate's insurance premium. The insurance premium is one of the largest single line items in most body corporate administration fund budgets, particularly in coastal or flood-prone locations where premiums have increased substantially over recent years.</p>

      <p>The insurance premium and the sum insured for the building are recorded in the body corporate's financial statements and are typically set out in the annual general meeting agenda and minutes. Sellers who want to understand their building's insurance position before listing should request the most recent annual general meeting minutes from the body corporate manager, which will include the insurer, the sum insured, and the premium paid.</p>

      <p>The certificate of currency, which is the formal document confirming that the insurance policy is in force, is also available from the body corporate manager on request. Buyers' solicitors and lenders sometimes request a copy of the certificate of currency as part of their due diligence. Having it on hand before listing means you can provide it quickly when asked, which avoids delays during the conditional period.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The underinsurance issue: why it matters more than it used to</h2>
      <p>Underinsurance in body corporates has become a more prominent concern following a series of natural disaster events in Queensland and across Australia. A building is underinsured when the sum insured is materially below what it would actually cost to demolish the existing structure and rebuild it to its current standard at today's construction costs. If such a building suffers a total or near-total loss, the body corporate's insurance payout covers only a portion of the true replacement cost, and the balance must be funded by the lot owners through a special levy or other means.</p>

      <p>Construction costs in Queensland have increased significantly over recent years, and many body corporate policies were last reviewed for replacement cost adequacy several years ago. A building insured based on a valuation from 2019 or 2020 may be carrying a significant underinsurance gap relative to current replacement costs. Buyers, particularly those who have purchased in other states or who are well-informed about strata property, are increasingly aware of this risk and may ask specific questions about when the sum insured was last independently reviewed.</p>

      <p>Sellers cannot control what the body corporate has done about underinsurance, but they can be prepared to discuss it honestly if it comes up. If the building has had a recent independent replacement cost assessment and the sum insured reflects current costs, that is a positive fact to communicate. If the sum insured has not been reviewed recently, it is worth raising with your body corporate manager before listing so you understand the position.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Claims history and what it signals to buyers</h2>
      <p>A buyer's solicitor conducting a body corporate records search will have access to the body corporate's insurance claims history, including the nature of claims made and whether they were paid. Multiple insurance claims, particularly for recurring issues such as water ingress, structural cracking, or fire system failures, can raise questions about the building's maintenance standard and the adequacy of prior remediation.</p>

      <p>A single significant claim following a well-documented weather event is generally less concerning to buyers than a pattern of claims that suggests chronic building problems. A building that has made a successful claim for storm damage, received the payout, and carried out the repairs is in a better position than one that has made repeated claims for the same issue without a clear resolution.</p>

      <p>Sellers should review the body corporate records for any recent claims before listing, so they are not caught off guard if a buyer raises the claims history. If there have been significant claims and associated repairs, being able to confirm that the repairs were properly completed and signed off by a licensed builder reduces the buyer's concern about residual risk.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to prepare before listing</h2>
      <p>Before your unit or townhouse goes to market, the practical steps related to body corporate insurance are straightforward. Request the most recent certificate of currency from the body corporate manager, confirm the sum insured and when it was last reviewed, check whether there are any current or recent claims on the policy, and confirm the annual insurance premium and what it represents as a component of the quarterly levy.</p>

      <p>If any of that information raises questions you cannot answer clearly, discuss it with your solicitor and agent before the listing goes live. A buyer who asks about insurance at an open home and receives a clear, confident answer from the agent is less likely to make it a condition of their offer than a buyer who has to chase the information down during the conditional period. Preparation on this front is low-cost and removes a predictable source of friction.</p>

